beer_description: Our homage to the beers that have quenched the thirst of Belgian farm workers for centuries. Brewed with barley, wheat and rice and fermented at high temperatures with a special blend of four different yeast strains, Saison is fruity and slightly tart, with a dry finish that makes it that rarest of treats???a beer as refreshing as it is complex.

beer_description: This thirst-quenching ?export style? brew is crafted the way domestic blonde ales were made 100 years ago. The natural sweetness of the malt dominates this smooth ale, making it ? what we alternately call the ?Ultimate Hockey Beer? or the ?Ultimate Cottage Beer? (depending on the season).
This American-style pale ale is brewed with three types of hops, producing a smooth flavor with a hoppy finish. Best Florida Beer Championships 2003 - Pipers Pale Ale ? Voted Best Florida Beer 2003
A medium-bodied brown English ale with a toasted, nutty and slightly bitter flavor.

Originally developed in the late 1700's, British breweries would send beer via sail to the troops and British expatriates in India. With a whopping hop aroma and finish, married to dry but full maltiness this ale will remind you of those traditional ales. The copper color, East Kent Golding's hops and moderate carbonation add to its authenticity as a English IPA.

Draper IPA is a well balanced IPA fermented with British yeast and a generous amount of hops added to the kettle and added during fermentation. Crystal and Munich malt add to the rich complexity of this flavorful IPA.
A refreshing and fun unfiltered Belgian style... brewed with varietal Orange Blossom honey, coriander and dried orange peel.

RETIRED - 2017 Checkins are probably Raspberry White. 
--||--||--
A golden wheat beer brewed with the finest North American malted barley and wheat. It?s then lightly hopped with the choicest European varieties. This smooth, crisp golden wheat beer is then finished with a hint of raspberry. Enjoy this beer any time of year.

The colour comes from dark roasted barley, balanced with just the right amount of sweet, rolled oatmeal. 

We mill both right here in the brewery, giving us complete control over flavour and freshness. The true taste of malt shines through, balanced by the sweetness of pure Scottish heather honey.

Piney, citrus hop notes combine with rich roast and alcohol heat. Flavor is full of complexity from a heavy hop addition and a rich grain bill. Espresso, bitter chocolate, grapefruit rind, and earth hot character. Bitter finish.

"Hand-crafted Double Dutch Ale".
Translates as 'Thunder and Lightning'.
Note: This is NOT the 6.2% Dutch lager of the same name.

A strong dark ale brewed with the 11 herbs and spices traditionally used in curing pastrami: Mustard Seed, Bay Leaf, Red Pepper, Coriander, Ginger, Allspice, Clove, Caraway Seed, Tellicherry Black Peppercorn, Cinnamon & Nutmeg + Rye, Dark Candi Sugar & some Smoked Malt.

This American style Pale Ale represents the quintessential microbrewery beer. Traditional Pale Ale styles are fused together to give a pungent floral and citrus aroma, with a complex malt palette and pleasant late bitterness.

This big NW IPA might just put a spell on you! With a burnt, golden-orange color, 6 malts and 4 hops varieties, this beer is enchanting. The up-front hammering of NW hops swirls around with the sweet malt body of one mouthful at a time, producing a light and crisp finish with just a hint of dryness that leaves you wanting more.
This northwest style pale ale is a confident beer with citrusy character,balanced with layers of malty goodness.

Taste true liquid luxury in this decadent and nuanced Belgian-style quad. Pear and apricot aromas blend with caramel, fruit and spice flavors in the full-bodied amber ale.

Warming alcohol notes mix with a lot of fruity fermentation profile on the nose. Big and bold, this beer is a boozy, savory treat. Rich caramel, clove, banana warming.

Original Pub Style harkens back to the very first brews Gritty's produced at our Portland Brew Pub back in 1988. "We wanted to make a beer that captures what made people fall in love with craft brewing in the first place; a fresh, classic pale ale with plenty of hop character." says Brewmaster Ed Stebbins. "This is the kind of beer that really started the whole Maine brewing revolution."
Original Pub Style is a light copper-colored medium-bodied with a nice dry bite at the finish. A subtle combination of Cascade and Willamette hops give this ale a fine floral aroma and a slightly fruity aftertaste. The taste captures the freshness of a hand-crafted brew pub ale that goes right from the conditioning tank to your glass! Original Pub Style is a year-round release available in six and twelve packs all over the great state of Maine, and on draft at Gritty's Portland and Freeport brew pubs.

Dixie Lager uses lightly roasted two
row barley malts, rice, and Cascade hops; the result is a crisp and flavorful beer. A century of New Orleans' brewing tradition lives today in every bottle and keg of Dixie Lager.

A Belgian Dubbel, a style that originated in the monasteries in the Middle Ages. This beer is rich, malty and raisiny with a touch of caramel flavor. Being one of our bigger beers this should be enjoyed in moderation.
A rich chestnut brown color with a nutty roasted malt caramel and chocolate aromas. Often brewed for the holidays, we christened the brew the "Nut Before Christmas."

Fruity beer with rich taste made by packaging "Weizen", the traditional beer in the South Germany made of over 50 % of wheat malt, without filtering beer yeast. Blue bottle with modern design brings out table coordinates.
Actually a pale ale made with cascade hops.

beer_description: Pilsner, label is in japanese :(
A classic NW style IPA, Hop Diggidy has a smooth pale malt background and a full round hop profile. Dry hopping insures an aromatic and lasting hop finish. Our best selling ale.
This traditionally brewed, award-winning Kolsch beer is straw colored, crisp, and refreshing, similar to a lager in many respects. Thus is actually a light German ale.

This innovative ale, burnished chestnut in color, contains the malt characteristics of an ESB without the typical bitterness. Lighter carbonation highlights the oak-aged flavor and its enduring tones of toasted vanilla and spice.

Our Imperial Stout is infused with fair-trade, organic coffee from a local roaster, Jobella, and aged for 6 months in a combination of Bourbon, retired Firestone Union and wine barrels. Black Xantus packs a powerful punch.
Anne is brewed with Elder Flowers, whole cone hops and Belgian malt. This is a draft only offering, keg conditioned.
Porter aged in Stranahan's whiskey barrels.  Awesome!
2010 winner of Brew at Choc's Home. Outstanding quality and complex flavors, also creative and ambitious.
A full-bodied, copper India Pale Ale. Fairly strong alcohol content and an aggressive fresh hop quality.

beer_description: The farmhouse ale, originally brewed for the workers of Wallonia, the country's French-speaking region. This version begins with a blend of European pilsner malts, a touch of malt and Nobel malts. These ingredients provide a vibrant palate, allowing the expressive Saison yeast to crate a truly unique flavor profile.
An Historical Porter, aged in barrels and enhanced with Bret. A smooth ale with hints of leather, cherries and chocolate. Simply beautiful!

beer_description: Since its release in 1995, Asahi Kuronama has become Japan?s favorite dark beer with its rich aroma and subtle sweetness. It is made from three types of dark roasted malt that each gives a different characteristic flavor according to how it is roasted and toasted. ?Dark malt? produces the distinct fragrance of dark beer. ?Crystal malt?imparts a delicate sweetness, and ?Munich malt? adds a fullness of taste. The exquisite blend of these three types of malt maximizes the goodness of each and creates Asahi Kuronama?s distinct richness and smoothness.
Kirin Ichiban Shibori is the name in the Japanese Market, whilst Kirin Ichiban is the name for export. 100% malt beer.

beer_description: Why Rye? This assertively flavorful grain is more often associated with whiskey than with ales. Even in that arena, it has largely been eclipsed by corn and barley, the sources of bourbon and scotch. But when we procured some seasoned barrels from our friends at Templeton Rye, we asked ourselves, ?Why not?? Why not brew a rich, tawny rye ale, then mellow it in the warmth of charred oak rye whiskey casks? Two kinds of malted rye provide spicy sweetness, giving way to notes of caramelized wood and the citrusy tang of Perle, Magnum, and Saphir hops before easing into a dry, lingering finish.

Our flagship brew highlights barrel-fermented batches from our patented Firestone Union blended with beer fermented in stainless steel.  It opens with a biscuity toasted malt aroma and a hint of oak and vanilla.  Pale malts create a smooth malty middle with ribbons of caramel, English toffee and toasted oak.  A tribute to English pales traditionally fermented in cask.
